  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (money laundering criminal offenses)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (monetary transactions in criminal proceeds)\n- Title III of the USA PATRIOT Act (enhanced reporting requirements)\n\n3. Regulatory Bodies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Civil and criminal prosecutions\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the disguising of illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. They require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs.\n\nEach state may also have additional money laundering statutes complementing federal laws.",
